From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] usb: xhci-aeolia: route Baikal IRQ through apcie_assign_irqs

Diagnosis from the 5th boot
(checkpoint/docs/uart-boot-2026-05-08-6x-bpcie-non-fatal.log + the
new boot at line 26778 with msleep(50) settle delay):

  [    7.058456] xhci_aeolia 0000:00:14.7: new USB bus registered, ...   ← buses up
  [    7.119292] usb usb1: New USB device found, idVendor=1d6b           ← root hubs OK
  [    7.158316] hub 1-0:1.0: USB hub found, 2 ports detected            ← all 4 root hubs alive
  ...
  [   14.484468] xhci_aeolia 0000:00:14.7: Error while assigning
                  device slot ID: Command Aborted                        ← 5+s after bus reg

The 5+ second gap between bus registration and Command Aborted is
exactly the kernel's TRB_RING_TIMEOUT (5 s) for command completion.
That signature points at IRQ delivery, not controller setup: the xHCI
host completes the ENABLE_SLOT command and fires its MSI to notify
the kernel, but the MSI never gets delivered to the right handler,
so xhci_handshake() times out and aborts the command.

The current xhci_aeolia_probe takes a Baikal-only branch that calls
`pci_alloc_irq_vectors(... PCI_IRQ_MSIX | PCI_IRQ_MSI)` directly,
bypassing the BPCIe glue's MSI domain. On Aeolia/Belize the standard
glue path runs via apcie_assign_irqs(). On Baikal that helper now
delegates to bpcie_assign_irqs() (since the bpcie cascade fix landed).

Just always use apcie_assign_irqs() for both. It does the right thing
on Aeolia/Belize/Baikal alike now, and routes through the per-function
MSI domain that bpcie_create_irq_domain() set up for function 14.7.

Source: rmuxnet/ps4-linux-12xx 8f2f907b
("usb: xhci-aeolia: Define extra_priv_size and enforce apcie IRQ
assignment").

Note: rmuxnet's commit also adds `.extra_priv_size = sizeof(struct
xhci_hcd)` to xhci_aeolia_overrides — but that line is already present
in our base (it never got removed because we didn't apply rmuxnet's
dcf8b509 that originally removed it).

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <17146298+meerzulee@users.noreply.github.com>
---
 drivers/usb/host/xhci-aeolia.c | 19 ++++++++++++-------
 1 file changed, 12 insertions(+), 7 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/usb/host/xhci-aeolia.c b/drivers/usb/host/xhci-aeolia.c
--- a/drivers/usb/host/xhci-aeolia.c
+++ b/drivers/usb/host/xhci-aeolia.c
@@ -409,13 +409,18 @@ static int xhci_aeolia_probe(struct pci_dev *dev, const struct pci_device_id *id
 	}
 	pci_set_drvdata(dev, axhci);

-	if (dev->device == PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_BAIKAL_XHCI) {
-		axhci->nr_irqs = retval = pci_alloc_irq_vectors(dev, NR_DEVICES, INT_MAX,
-			PCI_IRQ_MSIX | PCI_IRQ_MSI);
-	}
-	else {
-		axhci->nr_irqs = retval = apcie_assign_irqs(dev, NR_DEVICES);
-	}
+	/*
+	 * Always go through the PS4 glue's IRQ assignment.  On Aeolia/Belize
+	 * apcie_assign_irqs() runs the apcie code; on Baikal it delegates to
+	 * bpcie_assign_irqs() (see drivers/ps4/ps4-apcie.c).  The previous
+	 * Baikal-specific pci_alloc_irq_vectors() path bypassed the bpcie
+	 * MSI domain entirely, so command-completion IRQs from the xHCI
+	 * controller never reached the kernel — leading to the kernel's
+	 * 5-second TRB_RING_TIMEOUT and "Error while assigning device slot
+	 * ID: Command Aborted" on the first ENABLE_SLOT.
+	 * Source: rmuxnet/ps4-linux-12xx 8f2f907b.
+	 */
+	axhci->nr_irqs = retval = apcie_assign_irqs(dev, NR_DEVICES);

 	if (retval < 0) {
 		goto free_axhci;
